# Rule: Always align Build Version with `HEAD`

## Non-negotiable

**Every** time `summary.md` changes, lands in a commit, or you push/deploy (including partial doc-only pushes): run the verify step before considering the work done. Do not skip when ‚Äúonly a small edit‚Äù or ‚Äúwill fix later‚Äù‚Äîstale **`Build Version`** lines accumulate otherwise.

## Mandate

Whenever `summary.md` is edited, refreshed, or committed as part of documentation work, **`Build Version`** (backticks in the header) **must match** the current repository tip:

```bash
git rev-parse --short HEAD
```

On the default branch with a **clean** working tree, that value and **`Build Version`** **must be identical**.

## Verify (run every time ‚Äî after header edits, after commits touching `summary.md`, and immediately before `git push`)

```bash
git rev-parse --short HEAD
grep '^Build Version:' summary.md
```

If they disagree, update **`Build Version:`** to the short hash from `git rev-parse --short HEAD`, then commit.

## Git caveat

A commit‚Äôs id is not known until the commit exists, so the backtick value **cannot** equal **that same** commit‚Äôs hash. In practice: (1) set **`Build Version`** from **`git rev-parse --short HEAD`** **before** you commit `summary.md`; (2) **after** the commit, `HEAD` is a **new** id‚Äîupdate **`Build Version`** again in **one** small follow-up doc commit so the header matches the **new** tip; (3) that follow-up commit again advances `HEAD`, so the file may lag by **one** commit until the next sync. **Avoid stale hashes** (e.g. documenting an old tip when `main` has moved several commits ahead) by running the check whenever you touch the header or finish a merge.

## When editing the header

1. Run **`git rev-parse --short HEAD`** and set **`Build Version: \`<that-value>\`**.
2. Commit `summary.md` (and any other files) as usual.
3. If **`Build Version`** ‚âÝ **`git rev-parse --short HEAD`** on a clean tree, make **one** doc-only commit updating **`Build Version`** (and **`Last Updated`** if you like) to the current short hash, then push.

## Workflow: summary update ‚Üí commit ‚Üí deploy

Whenever you edit `summary.md`, commit, or deploy (alone or as the **Commit, Deploy and Update Summary** flow), keep **`Build Version`** aligned with **`HEAD`**:

1. **Before writing the header** ‚Äî Run `git rev-parse --short HEAD` and set **`Build Version: \`<value>\`** to that short hash (not an older hash from memory).
2. **After each commit that touches `summary.md`** ‚Äî On a clean tree, run the verify commands above. If they differ, make **one** doc-only commit updating **`Build Version`** (and **`Last Updated`** if appropriate).
3. **Before `git push` / deploy** ‚Äî Final check: clean working tree and **`grep '^Build Version:' summary.md`** matches **`git rev-parse --short HEAD`**. If not, sync `summary.md` and commit again, then push.

Deployed code is identified by the git revision you push; the documented **`Build Version`** should describe that same tip when the push includes `summary.md`.

## Relation to commit / deploy workflow

The **Commit, Deploy and Update Summary** rule (`.cursor/rules/commit-deploy-update-summary.mdc`) runs Phase 1 (summary) then Phase 2 (git + deploy). Phase 1 metadata and Phase 2 pre-push steps **must** follow this rule whenever **`Build Version`** is set or refreshed.
